The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       The City Diary
                  Two young women committed suicide in the city on Monday. Babita Das, 27, a resident of Shantipur in Nadia, jumped in front of a Dum Dum-bound Metro train at Girish Park station at 12.27pm. Metro Railway services were affected for 40 minutes. Trains plied between Tollygunge and Maidan during the period. In the evening, 21-year-old Chitralekha Mukherjee, a third-year commerce student of Surendranath College, hanged herself in her Thakurpukur house. Her mother found the body around 7.45pm. There was no suicide note.     Shakil Ahmed, 38, a spice merchant from Karachi in Pakistan, was arrested in Dum Dum on Monday afternoon. Police found that his visa had expired a month ago. According to a preliminary investigation, Ahmed has no terrorist link. He had visited the district enforcement branch office for extension of his visa.     The election of this years students general secretary of St Xaviers College was postponed on Monday afternoon after student groups clashed with each other before the polls. The new date of the election has not been declared.    Calcutta police will buy 10 more dogs for its dog squad in the next few months. The detective department has sent the proposal to the state government. The cops have sent four dogs in the squad to National Training Centre for Dogs in Gwalior. They would join the force within the next six months.    Visitors entry into Calcutta airport has been banned from Monday evening till August 20, 2008. An airport official said the ban was imposed in the wake of recent terror attacks.     A Druk Air flight from Dhaka to Paro in Bhutan was diverted to Calcutta because of bad weather. The flight landed in the city around 10.30am with 34 passengers and 8 crew members on board. It took off again around 12.45pm, said an airport official.    Randhir Kumar Jha, alias Pandit, was arrested around 12.15pm on Monday from the Bangur-VIP Road crossing. Nearly 20 kg of marijuana was found on him. Three cases of murder, two cases of attempted murder and several cases of extortion and burglary are lodged against him. He was earlier arrested in connection with murder charges and granted bail in June after serving a five-year sentence.    Emergency Management and Research Institute, a Secunderabad-based company that wants to set up emergency medical service points across the state, met officials at Writers Buildings on Monday. The company plans to set up call centres across the state and claims its employees can reach an accident spot in minutes. It currently functions in Andhra Pradesh, Uttarakhand and Gujarat.    Howrah-Yesvantpur Express will leave Howrah station at 11.30pm, instead of 10.35pm, from August 7 to August 31. The Yesvantpur-bound 2863 and 2864 Express trains from Howrah will continue to run along the diverted route via Jharsuguda-Sambalpur-Vizianagram and Vishakapatnam till August 31.    There was a bomb scare at Calcutta airport on Monday evening after a bag was found outside the domestic terminal. It contained tools.             
